estigators at classified facilities were often effectively prisoners, their movements restricted, their communication monitored. If they knew too much, or became a liability, their disappearance was simply another classified event. These aren't just statistics; these are lives. Minds capable of incredible breakthroughs, or terrifying mistakes, that were simply… extinguished. Their work, their research, their discoveries, all swallowed by the very secrecy they were sworn to uphold. The labs may be gone, but the human cost, the ethical dilemmas, and the lingering questions about their fates, continue to haunt us. What knowledge perished with them? And was their disappearance a consequence of their endeavors, or a deliberate act to ensure that knowledge remained forever lost?\",\n      \"visualCue\": \"Transition to a more human-focused narrative. Pictures of smiling individuals, then a slow zoom out to show them looking bewildered or afraid. Black and white photos of individuals who disappeared or died under mysterious circumstances (e.g., Frank Olson, various Soviet nuclear experts, British germ warfare experts). Overlay with newspaper clippings, \\\"Missing Person\\\" posters. Animated sequence: a person working late in a lab, a sudden power outage, a door creaking open, a shadowy figure, then an empty chair and a half-finished experiment. Visuals of isolated research stations, a single flickering light in a vast darkness. Focus on the psychological toll of working in absolute secrecy. A single, burning candle, then a gust of wind extinguishes it, leaving darkness.\",\n      \"assetType\": \"ai_gen\",\n      \"searchQueries\": [\n        \"Smiling scientist portrait\",\n        \"scientist looking bewildered afraid zoom out\",\n        \"Black and white photo disappeared scientist\",\n        \"vintage newspaper clipping mysterious death\",\n        \"missing person poster historical\",\n        \"Animated scientist working late lab disappearance\",\n        \"power